{"TopicId":193935,"ForumId":32,"TopicTitle":"TIL: decouplers fire away from the parent COM","CreatedByName":"Laie","CreatedById":110461,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-05-17T01:16:53Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Laie","CreatedById":110461,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-05-17T01:16:53Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022decoupling_vector.jpg\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002291.38\u0022 height=\u0022768\u0022 width=\u0022841\u0022 src=\u0022http://ksp.schnobs.de/stuff/decoupling_vector.jpg\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nA decoupler\u0027s force moves stuff away from the parent. Until just now, I wasn\u0027t aware that the game is quite literal about this.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt appears that the force always moves away from the parent part\u0027s center (\u003Cabbr title=\u0022Center of Mass\u0022\u003ECoM\u003C/abbr\u003E or origin, I don\u0027t know -- for most parts it\u0027s the same either way). It is definitely not the parent vessel \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Center of Mass\u0022\u003ECoM\u003C/abbr\u003E, but the parent part.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027ve only done limited testing and cannot say if the force simply goes through the decoupler, or if it is more complicated than that.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222020-05-17T01:35:24Z\u0022 title=\u002205/17/2020 01:35  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EMay 17, 2020\u003C/time\u003E by Laie\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"AHHans","CreatedById":197939,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-05-17T14:30:44Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223786398\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193935\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221589678213\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022110461\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Laie\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n13 hours ago, Laie said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt appears that the force always moves away from the parent part\u0027s center\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nWell, as far as I can tell that\u0027s \u003Cs\u003Eonly\u003C/s\u003E true for the Structural Pylon. The o\u003Cs\u003Ether (regular)\u003C/s\u003E [Edit]\u003Cstrong\u003Eradial\u003C/strong\u003E[/Edit] decouplers behave as expected, i.e. they push themselves (and anything connected to them) away in the direction they are pointing:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u0022J5qnxeG.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002256.25\u0022 height=\u0022576\u0022 style=\u0022width:800px;height:auto;\u0022 width=\u00221024\u0022 src=\u0022https://imgur.com/J5qnxeG.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00225cTq3Pd.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002256.25\u0022 height=\u0022576\u0022 style=\u0022width:800px;height:auto;\u0022 width=\u00221024\u0022 src=\u0022https://imgur.com/5cTq3Pd.png\u0022\u003E\u003Cbr\u003E\n(Notice how both structural pylons are in front of the smoke from their decoupling.)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n[Edit:] O.K. I now also tested the TD-06 and TD-12 stack decouplers, and they also behave as described by \u003Ca contenteditable=\u0022false\u0022 data-ipshover=\u0022\u0022 data-ipshover-target=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/110461-laie/\u0026amp;do=hovercard\u0022 data-mentionid=\u0022110461\u0022 href=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/profile/110461-laie/\u0022 rel=\u0022\u0022\u003E@Laie\u003C/a\u003E \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:/\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/ZNGIcon1.png\u0022 title=\u0022:/\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222020-05-17T14:39:54Z\u0022 title=\u002205/17/2020 02:39  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EMay 17, 2020\u003C/time\u003E by AHHans\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"KerikBalm","CreatedById":91917,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-05-18T07:10:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHmm, very interesting.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe small hardpoint and structural pylon are very similar in design and appearance (just different sizes), does the small pylon behave like this too?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"AHHans","CreatedById":197939,"CreatedDateTime":"2020-05-18T07:37:27Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223786910\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022193935\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221589785832\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002291917\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022KerikBalm\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n23 minutes ago, KerikBalm said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\ndoes the small pylon behave like this too?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nEasy to test. So, yes.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAnd btw. a cubic octagonal strut counts as a parent part (even tough it is \u0022physicsless\u0022). That gives you some control when you need the ejection force to be in a certain direction.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}